The FT-IR results of NCQDs showed several stretching vibrations of C-OH at 3400 cm−1, C–H at 2918 cm−1, C = C at 1579 cm−1, and bending vibrations of C–H at 1395 cm−1. Additionally, due to the N doping, N–H stretching vibrations were observed at 3231 cm−1, along with N–H bending vibrations at 1190 cm−1 (Fig. i) [32]. The XPS results showed a characteristic peak of N 1 s at 399.7 eV, signifying a surface doping level of 4.19 % for this element (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). The distinct peaks at 285.3 eV and 532.4 eV are attributable to C 1 s and O 1 s, respectively. The fitted spectrum is presented in Fig. 1j ∼ l. The high-resolution XPS analysis of C 1 s exhibited three peaks at 284.3 eV, 285.3 eV, and 286.0 eV, corresponding to C–C/C = C, C-N, and C-O, respectively [33]. Regarding the high-resolution XPS of N 1 s, three energy binding peaks at 388.6 eV, 399.5 eV, and 400.9 eV were observed, representing pyridine, pyrrole, and graphite nitrogen, respectively (Fig. 1k) [34]. The high resolution of the O 1 s spectrum of NSCDs clearly exhibited three peaks, centered at 531.2, 532.1, and 532.8 eV, which were assigned to O–H, C-O, and C-O, respectively [35].

After 12 days of fermentation, the remaining HAs in the system were extracted and tested. It was found that the characteristic structural content of HAs, including –OH at 3100 ∼ 3500 nm−1 and carbonyl and aromatic carbonyl amides at 1500 ∼ 1660 nm−1, decreased in AD systems exposed to light exposure or NCQDs (
                              Fig. S3
                           ). These results indicated that light and NCQDs with photo response accelerated the degradation of the solid portion of HAs and DOM (some originating from HAs).
